<font color="#FF0000">BEAST OF MANY NAMES</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 27 11:40:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The Beast,<br><br>
This is long, but reflect on the parts.  Ed, and Cook will understand.  Marines, seals, and others know.<br><br>
We have focused on the PTSD as something always around, but predominantly a Vietnam thing.  We have dismissed that the beast was known by other names.  WWI called it shell shocked.  WWII called it battle fatigue.  Other wars other names.  Korea other vague references, the massive POW thing.  All indicating something unknown.  Sweep it under the rug.<br><br>
I have personally talked at length to vets of all these wars.  They suffer quietly.  The older generations, my Dad included never admitted weakness.  You need only look in their eyes to see the images of what we talk about.  I have watched as they seek their quiet time.  When the wrong subject surfaced,  I watched my Dad walk away from me into the edge of the woods and stand with his back to me.  Never cried or showed emotion. (Special Ops WWII Pacific ahead of the lines)<br><br>
Some of us were protected more by their training.  I come from a family with some history.  Lessons learned were passed on.  I was conditioned in the arts of weapons.  I was taught to shut down feelings and control fear, temper rage and focus on the target.  Live in the forests, read trails, find food, be totally sufficient.  Started before school.  Little did I know that I was being conditioned from what he felt.<br><br>
My neighbor talked to me about all the mechanisms he used in the Korean POW camps (a Marine) and how he survived.  He talked I listened.<br><br>
I was trained in the military in certain camps on the control of the mind.  Subjected to real torture to  test my breaking point.  Lost my reality, learned that all who would do me harm are my enemy.  I know what it is like to feel my ankle slowly stressed until the ligaments start to break and you begin to shut down the pain centers.  I have seen men break in the conditioning and one hang himself with razor wire to escape his demons.  I was held to ground with men stomping on my back, while one ran a clip from an AKA beside my head.  Took away my stereo forever.  The ringing never leaves.  The sound still brings hate to the surface.<br><br>
I parachuted into the sea in a storm only to find that to increase stress the LPUs had no charge.  No flotation device and being dragged backwards in the wind.  Full gear, no LPU and raft with no charge.  Control fear and go to work just to survive.<br><br>
Physical conditioning, from years of training let me know I could survive.  Controlled fear.  I still must maintain physical intensity to this day.<br><br>
To bring this to a closure.  Our country knew how to protect us with mental conditioning.  Certain schools did it then.  Some were shut down because of their brutality and fatality rate.  Others still exist.  I propose the problem was that time was limited and the costs were high.  Most went in untrained and physically deficient to cope with what was coming.  They chose those with the highest risk to self and country.  Let the others go.  Do so to this day.<br><br>
Marines were trained for a reason.  Snipers, seals, rangers, all with a special emphasis.  The common grunt, fair game.<br><br>
Even the best training can not totally protect.  Mine was close.  A type of mental conditioning.  Doc would be interested.<br><br>
Comments?<br>

